attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Cranmer Green in Walsham le Willows (Suffolk), and perhaps also from other places similarly named, such as Cranmer Hall in Sculthorpe (Norfolk), Cranmore in Shalfleet (Isle of Wight), Cranmer Bottom in Selborne and Cranmore in Aldershot (both Hampshire), and East and West Cranmore (Somerset), all named from Old English <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pool’ or <i>mōr</i> ‘moor, marshy ground’. See also   Cranmore  , with which there may have been some confusion."],"variants":[{"name":"Cranmore","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Cranmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Alice Cranmer was born in 1386, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas de Cranmer in 1407, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1461, in her hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1386–1461":"1386–1461","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1386":"1386","November 1450":"